annotation.TEXT: The “head shake” sound frequently heard in Looney Tunes animated shorts was created by renowned voice artist Mel Blanc.
Solzhenitsyn himself was imprisoned for 8 years for insulting Soviet dictator Joseph Stalin in a letter to a friend.
The film Clue, based on the classic board game, was released with three different endings, in which various characters turned out to be the murderer.
A parody of Clint Eastwood’s famous line from the 1971 film Dirty Harry.
“A man’s got to know his limitations” is a line from the Dirty Harry film Magnum Force.
In the Old Testament, Jezebel was the wife of Israeli King Ahab. She introduced the worship of Baal into Israel, and has come to personify the wicked woman.
Prange Way was a chain of discount department stores in the Midwest.
Gymkata was an enjoyably bad film starring world champion gymnast Kurt Thomas, who defeats the bad guys with the help of randomly placed gymnastics equipment.
Environmental artist Christo specializes in massive outdoor installations. In 1991 he installed 3,100 large yellow umbrellas in 2 valleys for 18 days.
A line from the Doobie Brothers song “Takin’ It to the Streets.”
A paraphrase of a line from the Charles Dickens novel Oliver Twist.
A Dilly Bar is offered at Dairy Queens: a disc of soft-serve ice cream coated in chocolate and served on a stick. It was created by the owner of a DQ in Moorhead, MN.
On the ‘60s TV show Batman, the Dynamic Duo “climbed” up buildings by grabbing ropes fastened to a wall and walking across a painted floor with the camera turned sideways.
Also in Snausages? Propylene glycol, a food preservative and an ingredient in some types of antifreeze.
Where Eagles Dare is a film about a WWII commando team raiding a mountain fortress in Germany to rescue a general.
A paraphrase of a line from the film The Abyss, as Ed Harris is trying to resuscitate the drowned Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio.
The Trapp Family Singers were a group of Austrian performers who fled the Nazis in 1938 and emigrated to the US. Their story was told in The Sound of Music.
People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals is an animal rights group that stages protests, airs ads, and files lawsuits on behalf of animals everywhere.
A squib is a small explosive device. In moviemaking, very small squibs are used to simulate bullet impacts.
The film Carnival of Souls starred Candace Hilligloss as the sole survivor of a deadly car accident. Director Herk Harvey usually made educational shorts, including two that ran on MST3K.
Tyrone Power was a Hollywood leading man in the ‘30s & ‘40s. He starred in swashbucklers like The Mark of Zorro and The Black Swan.
And now for your enjoyment…the fully-annotated The Painted Hills!
Snausages has another line of products called Snaw Somes, longer than the typical bite-sized treat.
Moses is a biblical figure who led the Israelites out of slavery in Egypt to the Promised Land.
One Day in the Life of Ivan Denisovich is a novel by Russian author Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn that follows a man through a typical day as a prisoner in a Soviet labor camp.
Kris Kringle is another name for Santa Claus; the name comes from the word Christkind, or Christ child.
Standard Snausages today are called Snausages in a Blanket.
Pippi Longstocking is the heroine of a series of children’s books: a girl with gravity-defying braids, superhuman strength, and enormous wealth.
The bearded, burly Victor French played Isaiah Edwards on Little House on the Prairie and reunited with Little House star Michael Landon on Highway to Heaven.
The film Oh! Heavenly Dog starred Chevy Chase as a PI who is murdered and sent back in the body of a dog (canine star Benji) to solve the crime.
A line from the film It’s a Mad, Mad, Mad, Mad World.
Tom Bombadil is a character in J.R.R. Tolkien’s fantasy epic The Lord of the Rings.
A line from the song “Dominique” by the Singing Nun, aka Sister Luc-Gabrielle, a Belgian nun in the Dominican order.
The Roy Rogers Show, which ran in the ‘50s, had cowboys riding horses and firing six-shooters alongside people driving cars and talking on telephones.
“It works every time” is the longtime slogan for Colt 45 malt liquor, used mainly in ‘80s-era ads featuring actor Billy Dee Williams.
The missing man formation is a military tradition at funerals for pilots, astronauts, and other dignitaries.
An imitation of John Cleese as hotel owner Basil Fawlty on the classic British TV show Fawlty Towers.
The Missouri Synod is a conservative Lutheran sect headquartered in St. Louis, MO.
An imitation of Johnny Weissmuller, who played Tarzan the Ape Man in a series of films from 1932-48.
Did we somehow miss one? Be sure to let us know in the comments!

General Mills stole the idea for Bisquick baking mix from a train chef, who pre-mixed his biscuit batter so he could bake them fresh every day.
Also Sprach Zarathustra was both named after and inspired by a novel by Friedrich Nietzsche. The famous fanfare used in 2001 is from the first section, “Sunrise.”
The Incredible Journey is a book/film about a cat and two dogs who get separated from their owners on vacation and manage to make their way home.
A riff on Dustin Hoffman’s famous improvised line in the film Midnight Cowboy: “I’m walkin’ here! I’m walkin’ here!”
The Shootist starred John Wayne as a gunfighter with terminal cancer looking to go out in style. It was Wayne’s last film; he died—of stomach cancer—3 years later.
Iron sights are a feature on firearms, crossbows, or telescopes that allow you to aim when they’re aligned: two pieces of metal, one on either end of the device.
Snausages are available in several flavors: beef, beef & cheese, bacon & cheese, and most recently peanut butter & apple.
Gideons International is the group behind all those Bibles in hotel rooms. The first Bibles were placed in the Superior Hotel in Montana in 1908.
Home perms were introduced in the ‘40s, with brands like Toni, Lilt, and Bobbi. They were so popular beauty salons tried to get laws passed banning them.
A paraphrase of a line from the Alfred Hitchcock classic North by Northwest. The monument in question: Mt. Rushmore.
Rat Packer Joey Bishop also played a Native American in a film: Dean Martin’s sidekick Kronk in the comic Western Texas Across the River.
A line from the 1975 film Monty Python and the Holy Grail.
A line from the song “Tommy Can You Hear Me” from The Who’s rock opera Tommy.
In 1966, Charles Whitman murdered 14 people and wounded more than 30 others with a rifle from the UT Austin bell tower before he was killed by police.
A line from the film It’s a Wonderful Life.
A parody of a late ‘70s/early ‘80s ad slogan for Purina Puppy Chow: “Puppy Chow for a full year, till he’s full grown.”
In a host segment in MST3K Episode 404, Teenagers from Outer Space, Dr. Forrester performs mouth-to-mouth on a Resusci Annie doll and remarks, “That’s an odd taste.”
Actor Jeff Chandler was nominated for an Oscar for his role as Apache chief Cochise in the Jimmy Stewart Western Broken Arrow.
Gaines-Burgers was a brand of soft, crumbly dog food that looked like raw hamburger, only drier. It was discontinued in the ‘90s.
Lincoln was assassinated shortly after the war’s end by disgruntled Southerner John Wilkes Booth.
Did we somehow miss a reference? Let us know in the comments!
CD stands for Certificate of Deposit, a financial product in which a sum of money earns a set rate of interest over a set period of time.
In 2015 the brand was sold to the J.M. Smucker Co. (yes, the jelly people).
Early in the 1904 J.M. Barrie play Peter Pan, Peter loses his shadow when the Darlings’ window slams shut on it.
The Life and Times of Grizzly Adams was a film starring Dan Haggerty as a man who lives in the mountains with his pet bear. A TV show, TV movies, and films followed.
A paraphrase of the theme song to the Bat Masterson TV Western.
A ‘60s-era jingle for the Chef Boyardee product.
Snow globes or snow domes are plastic balls with winter scenes inside, filled with water and confetti, so that when shaken it appears to be “snowing.”
The first digital matte painting was featured in the 1985 film Young Sherlock Holmes.
Grecian Formula is a hair dye for men that promises to gradually get rid of gray hair over a period of weeks.
“Mola Ram, prepare to meet Kali—in hell!” is a line from the film Indiana Jones and the Temple of Doom.
German-born actress Marlene Dietrich’s first major role was as a cabaret singer in Der blaue Engel (The Blue Angel).
In Purina Chuck Wagon dog food ads in the ‘70s, a dog would chase a tiny horse and covered wagon team through the house and into a kitchen cabinet.
Recording artist Ken Nordine is best known for his Word Jazz series of spoken-word albums, which were popular in the late ‘50s and ‘60s.
Horiatiki, or Greek salad, was created in the ‘60s to cater to the tourist trade. The American version is similar, but adds romaine lettuce to the mix.
A paraphrase of a line from the film An American Werewolf in London.
New Age music, popular in the ‘80s & ‘90s, was often mixed with field recordings of ambient nature sounds—chirping crickets, ocean waves, etc.
Denver Pyle was a portly, bearded character actor best known for playing Uncle Jesse on the TV show The Dukes of Hazzard.
At absolute zero (0 degrees Kelvin), nearly all molecular motion stops.
Alive: A rugby team’s plane crashes in the mountains, and the survivors must eat the dead to live.
Kitty Russell, or Miss Kitty (played by Amanda Blake), was the saloon owner on the TV series Gunsmoke.
In “The Spanish Inquisition” skit from Monty Python’s Flying Circus, Cardinal Ximénez (Michael Palin) keeps remembering additional points to whatever speech he’s trying to make.
Cousins Larry Appleton and Balki Bartokomous were the main characters on the TV sitcom Perfect Strangers.
Wild Hearts Can’t Be Broken is a film starring Gabrielle Anwar as a young runaway who wants to be a “diving girl” and ride diving horses.
A reference to MST3K Episode 104, Women of the Prehistoric Planet.
“This time ... it’s personal” was the tagline for the film Jaws: The Revenge.
A line from the Jethro Tull song “Thick as a Brick.”
In cross-section, the Frisbee is an airfoil, allowing it to fly for quite a distance. The phrasing is derived from a 13th-century proverb.
The original frozen Bomb Pops were red, white, and blue and had 3 different flavors: cherry, lime, and blue raspberry.
Carpenter Bruno Hauptmann was convicted of kidnapping and murdering Charles Lindbergh’s young son. He was executed in 1936.
By the time Kenny Rogers retired in 2016, he had sold more than 100 million albums worldwide.
During David Spade’s stint on SNL in the ‘90s, he would mock super-thin supermodel Kate Moss by saying, “I had a rice cake today. I’m so naughty!”
Snausages produced a tie-in with the live action Scooby-Doo film when they introduced Scooby Snacks in 2002.
“Doughboy” was a slang term for a soldier in the US Army or Marine Corps, originating during the Mexican-American War and becoming widespread in WWI.
As pet obesity has risen, Snausages’ Snaw Somes have been targeted: three of the first four ingredients are sugars.
Despite the many, many jokes to the contrary, Timmy never did fall down a well on the Lassie TV show.
A line from the song “Wildfire,” performed by Michael Martin Murphey, about a woman who dies searching for her horse during a blizzard.
A reference to MST3K Episode 422, The Day the Earth Froze.
Mrs. Dash is a line of seasoning blends created by marketing exec Carol Bernick, who also considered naming the brand “Mrs. Pinch.”
That Girl was a TV show that starred Marlo Thomas as Ann Marie, an aspiring actress struggling to make it in NYC.
Do these guys not know any other dog treats? Beggin’ Strips? Pup-Peroni? Milk-Bones? Anything!
Mackenna’s Gold is a film about an outlaw who kidnaps a marshal because he believes the lawman knows the location of a hidden vein of gold.
Michael McDonald was the bearded lead singer for the Doobie Brothers on songs like “What a Fool Believes” and “Takin’ It to the Streets.”
Alex Trebek is the longtime host of the TV game show Jeopardy, which first aired in 1984.
Dutch elm disease is a fungus that attacks elm trees, sometimes killing them within a month. It is spread by the elm bark beetle, which carries the fungus spores on its shell.
The Firm is a John Grisham novel about a young lawyer who gets a job at a law firm and discovers it’s controlled by the Mafia. It was made into a movie starring Tom Cruise.
Planet Hollywood is an international restaurant chain featuring movie memorabilia. It is partly owned by Hollywood celebrities.
The Most Dangerous Game is a film starring Joel McCrea and Fay Wray as shipwrecked passengers on a mysterious island whose owner hunts humans for sport.
“My way or the highway” dates back only to the late ‘60s/early ‘70s. Some sources attribute it to baseball manager Sparky Anderson.
Divinity is an old-fashioned candy made from egg whites, corn syrup, and sugar, and sometimes dried fruit or nuts. It’s usually white and tastes kind of like the nougat in candy bars.
A line from the sci-fi thriller Invasion of the Body Snatchers. Kevin McCarthy said the line in both the 1956 original and in a brief cameo in the 1978 remake.
The word “souvlaki” comes from souvla, meaning skewer, which is how the meat is cooked.
Actor Larry Hovis was best known for playing Sgt. Andrew Carter on the TV show Hogan's Heroes.
Frank Sutton played the irascible Sgt. Vince Carter on the ‘60s TV series Gomer Pyle, U.S.M.C.
A Current Affair was a TV “news” show in the US that specialized in celebrity gossip, lurid sex scandals, etc., hosted by Maury Povich.
Brought to you by the Official MST3K YouTube Channel.
Rutherford B. Hayes was the 19th US president, after a bitterly contested election decided by a panel of congressmen, who voted along strict party lines to declare him the victor.
In T.H. White’s novel The Once and Future King, Merlin turns a young Arthur into various animals to help prepare him to become king.
A line from “That’s the Way (I Like It),” a #1 hit for KC and the Sunshine Band in 1975.
A paraphrased line from the John Wayne Western True Grit.
A line from the James Bond film Octopussy, starring Roger Moore.
The Painted Hills: Fully annotated by The Official MST3K YouTube Channel.
A parody of a line from the film The Warriors, about battling street gangs in NYC.
A paraphrase of the Doobie Brothers song “What a Fool Believes.”
While Paul Revere warned Lexington about the British troops (saying “The regulars are coming out!”), Sam Prescott alerted Concord; Revere had been captured along the way.
He spends a lot of time singing in an irritating fashion.
The prototype for the Super Soaker water gun was built out of PVC pipe, Plexiglas, and a 2-liter soda bottle.
A water flume ride is an amusement park staple—Splash Mountain in Disneyland is one example.

This was among Curly’s many signature comedic sounds; lying on his side and spinning around was one of his physical shticks.
My Side of the Mountain: A young boy runs away to the mountains after his family cancels their planned vacation.
The Andrews Sisters (Patty, Laverne & Maxene) sang classic WWII-era hits such as “Boogie Woogie Bugle Boy.”
This charming little aphorism was told to Catholic schoolchildren to prevent masturbation. Specifically, it was St. Louis who got weepy over self-pleasuring.
RyKrisps were baked rye crackers made in Minneapolis. They were discontinued in 2015.
A paraphrase of a line from “Seattle,” the theme song to the TV show Here Come the Brides. Perry Como recorded a hit cover version in 1969.
Oh, for … Fine. Hang on. Um, did you know they used to make Snausages Breakfast Bites? They were bacon & egg flavored.
An imitation of Adam West as Batman.
A little doggie rendition of “The Hills Are Alive” from The Sound of Music.
This Old House is a home improvement show that first aired in 1979. For 10 years the host was the bearded, genial Bob Vila.
Damn it. In 2010, Snausages made football-shaped treats with the packaging themed for each of the NFL’s teams.
King Lear is a 1605 tragedy by William Shakespeare about a man who divides his kingdom among his daughters and is then driven mad by their ingratitude.
Lawn gnomes originated in Germany in the 19th century and became popular in the ‘30s after the release of Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs.
A parody of Groucho Marx’s famous line from the Marx Brothers film A Day at the Races: “Either he’s dead or my watch has stopped.”
With annotations provided by The Annotated MST website.
In 1976, French singer/actress Claudine Longet shot and killed her boyfriend, skier Spider Sabich. She claimed it was accidental and served only 30 days in prison.
Barbasol shaving cream was invented by a former MIT professor in 1919.
A paraphrase of the song “Sobbin’ Women” from Seven Brides for Seven Brothers. The musical is loosely based on the Roman myth of the Sabine women.
“I can’t believe I ate the whole thing” is a line from a ‘70s ad for Alka-Seltzer.
Sesame Street’s Big Bird sang a song in 1970 titled “ABC-DEF-GHI” in which he mistook the alphabet for one long word. The song has been reused in several episodes since then.
The sole studio album of British punk band the Sex Pistols was titled Never Mind the Bollocks, Here’s the Sex Pistols.
K2, at 28,251 feet, is the second-tallest mountain in the world, after Mt. Everest. “K9” is the designation for police dog units.
This comes from an old vaudeville routine that has been used by many comedians, including Abbott & Costello and the Three Stooges.
Dinty Moore is a brand of canned beef stew, but the name comes from a comic strip called “Bringing Up Father”—Moore was a tavern owner in the strip.
Robert Fulghum’s book All I Really Need to Know I Learned in Kindergarten contains such nuggets of wisdom as “Take a nap every afternoon.” It has sold 7 million copies.
Tom Wopat is best known for playing the part of Luke Duke on the TV series The Dukes of Hazzard.
In the early ‘90s, singer/actress Cher made an infomercial for Lori Davis hair products as a favor to a friend that made her the butt of jokes for more than a year.
An imitation of comedian Lou Costello of Abbot and Costello. When Costello had made a mess of things, he’d often declare: “I’m a bad boy.”
A line from the old form of the Catholic Mass; in 2008 the response was changed to “And with your spirit.”
An imitation of radio and TV sports announcers, who typically give the score and what portion of the game is being played, e.g., “10-3, at the half.”
A paraphrased line from the William Shakespeare play Hamlet (c. 1600).
N.B.: Pal’s trainer’s name was Rudd, not Russ. Rudd was short for Ruddell.
A classic line uttered by Colonel Wilhelm Klink (Werner Klemperer), the inept commander of the German POW camp in the TV show Hogan’s Heroes.
Paraphrased lyrics from the children’s song “Baby Bumblebee,” set to the tune of “The Arkansas Traveler,” the official state song of Arkansas from 1949-63.
The Lassie TV show had several theme songs, the most famous of which began with the fifth season: “The Whistler,” performed by Muzzy Marcellino.
The grunge look—torn jeans, big boots, flannel shirts—became popular in the early ‘90s along with Seattle bands like Nirvana.
A play on the saying “There’s gold in them thar hills!”; the phrase’s origins are unclear.
A line from the black comedy Heathers, which starred Winona Ryder and Christian Slater as a couple of teens who begin killing off popular students.
The famous 1967 film of Bigfoot walking through the forest was taken in Humboldt County, CA, just south of the Oregon border.
Kal Kan was a brand of canned dog food, but the manufacturer changed its name to Pedigree starting in 1988.
A famous scene in the film Scanners depicts a duel of sorts between two people with telekinetic abilities: the loser’s head explodes.
The screeching violin, viola, and cello theme from the infamous shower scene in Psycho was composed by Bernard Herrmann and titled “The Murder.”
The drachma was the basic unit of currency in Greece until it was replaced by the euro in 2002.
A riff on a line from Bill Hicks’ standup routine: “Jesus is back—and he’s pissed.”
“Refritos” is short for “frijoles refritos,” or refried beans. “Refried” is a misnomer – in this context “refrito” just means cooked, not fried, repeatedly or otherwise.
Legendary Hollywood animal trainers Frank and Rudd Weatherwax trained Pal, the original Lassie (seen here playing Shep), in addition to his successors.
National Velvet is a horse-racing movie starring Mickey Rooney and a 12-year-old Elizabeth Taylor.
Metamucil is a bulk fiber laxative made from psyllium husk, which is also used as a thickener for ice cream.
Paraphrased lyrics to Jimi Hendrix’s classic 1967 psychedelic rock anthem “Purple Haze.”
The Maclean book was adapted into a film starring Brad Pitt in 1992. It was nominated for three Oscars and won one.
Leon Trotsky helped lead the 1917 Communist revolution in Russia, but Stalin exiled him in 1929. He was assassinated in 1940 by a Stalinist agent wielding an ice axe.
In skiing, a “bunny hill” is a particularly gentle and unchallenging slope intended for beginning skiers and snowboarders.
Tarzan, the king of the jungle created by pulp author Edgar Rice Burroughs, had the ability to call on various beasts to help him when he needed them.
Across 11 films, 3 live TV series, and 2 radio shows, Lassie has been played by about 13 dogs, almost all descended from the original, Pal.
Juan Valdez, the longtime spokesperson for Colombian coffee growers, has been played by three different actors since his introduction in 1958.
Abraham Lincoln was the 16th US president, who famously guided the nation through the Civil War.
The song “Look for the Union Label” aired in an ad for the International Ladies’ Garment Workers’ Union in the ‘70s.
A parody of the famous first line of Charles Dickens’ novel A Tale of Two Cities. The cities in question: London and Paris.
An imitation of the song “Hoe-Down” in Rodeo, the ballet scored by Aaron Copland, aka the “Beef: It’s What’s for Dinner” music.
In the Simpsons episode “Itchy and Scratchy: The Movie,” a drawbridge opens and a man waiting to see the film plummets to his death, screaming, “I regret nothing!”
“Tastes as great as its name” is a ‘70s ad slogan for Old Milwaukee beer.
A parody of the climactic line from the 1951 horror flick The Thing from Another World.
A doppelgänger (double walker) is a spirit that looks just like you; in German folklore, seeing your doppelgänger is a sign that you will soon die.
An imitation of bumbling French policeman Inspector Clouseau (Peter Sellers), in the famous “Does your dog bite?” scene from The Pink Panther Strikes Again.
The historian who proposed Mt. Rushmore originally wanted it to feature western heroes like Buffalo Bill Cody and Lewis & Clark.
This is the main theme to the film The Great Escape, composed by Elmer Bernstein.
The Eiger is a mountain in the Swiss Alps; its northern face is one of the most dangerous climbs in that range, with at least 64 deaths since 1935.
In a Monty Python’s Flying Circus skit called “How to Recognize Different Parts of the Body,” an oft-repeated part of the body is “the naughty bits.”
A line from the song “I Feel Pretty” from the musical West Side Story.
The Weatherwax brothers also trained the dogs that played Old Yeller and Asta in The Thin Man.
Camille is a tearjerker starring Greta Garbo as a courtesan who nobly leaves her lover for his own good; at the end of the film she expires in his arms from tuberculosis.
The Nut Goodie was the first candy bar made by the Pearson’s Candy Co., based in St. Paul, MN.
Heathcliff is the anti-hero of Emily Brontë’s classic romantic novel Wuthering Heights, first published in 1847.
As film legend would have it, the original title of the Bond film Licence to Kill, “Licence Revoked,” was changed because producers feared Americans were too dumb to understand it.
An imitation of Curly Howard, the best known of the Three Stooges, who performed on stage and in many short films along with Moe and Shemp Howard and Larry Fine.
An imitation of the many ads for attorneys that air on late-night TV.
Othello is a 1603 tragedy by William Shakespeare about a Moorish general driven by jealousy to murder his faithful wife.
Lon Chaney Jr. was known for various horror films—particularly his portrayal of Larry Talbot in The Wolf Man.
A paraphrased line from The Princess Bride, a 1987 film based on the William Goldman novel (who also wrote the screenplay).
When Arthur Conan Doyle got sick of Sherlock Holmes, he had Holmes and Moriarty fall to their death off the top of Reichenbach Falls in Switzerland.
Dwarf tossing is a pub attraction in England and former British colonies, in which contestants compete to see how far they can throw a little person.
Obsession is a perfume manufactured by Calvin Klein. It was introduced in 1985.
King Arthur’s castle was first mentioned in Chrétien de Troyes’ 12th-century poem “Lancelot, the Knight of the Cart.”
Serial killer David Berkowitz, aka Son of Sam, told police his neighbor Sam had sent him orders to kill through Sam’s dog, a black Lab named Harvey.
The Eiger Sanction: An assassin joins a mountain climbing team and plots to kill one of its members.
Max Fleischer’s “Out of the Inkwell” animated shorts in the ‘20s began with a shot of a hand drawing with a fountain pen.
The bourbon whiskey Jim Beam was originally made by Jacob Beam; it was named Jim Beam after his great-grandson, who rebuilt the business after Prohibition.
The opening line to disgraced former President Richard M. Nixon’s memoirs.
A 1973 ad for Canadian Club whiskey told a dramatic tale of hang gliding off New Zealand’s Glacier Dome.
CorelDRAW is computer graphics software produced by the Corel Corporation since 1989.
Thanks for watching this fully-annotated presentation of The Painted Hills.
Unlike the more common Persian limes, the smaller Key limes produce yellow juice, making the filling in Key lime pie yellow as well.
When Helen Gurley Brown became editor of Cosmo in 1965 she began promoting her ideal that sex for women should be fun and guilt-free—a controversial stance at the time.
Tuttle also worked on North by Northwest, Twilight Zone, and Young Frankenstein, among others.
Natalie Wood got her start as a child actress in such films as Miracle on 34th Street.
Russell Means is a Native American activist who led the American Indian Movement in the ‘70s; he is also an actor (The Last of the Mohicans, Natural Born Killers).
The lambada is a Brazilian dance that was briefly popular in the US and Europe in 1989. The film Lambada, The Forbidden Dance came out in 1990 to capitalize on the fad.
A line from ‘70s TV ads for Shake ‘n Bake.
In scouring the web for more Snausage trivia, we found a support group forum for humans who like to snack on the treats.
Son of a … OK, so where do Snausages get their name? According to its introductory ad in 1984: “Sausage-style snacks!”
It actually was, although it was his middle name; his first name was William. His dad, a well-known silent-film actor, had the same name.
The phrase “milk of human kindness,” meaning to show care and compassion for others, originated in William Shakespeare’s 1606 play Macbeth.
As president, Hayes ended Reconstruction in the South and refused a nomination for a second term.
For the record, Joel, Tom, and Crow said the word “Snausage” 17 times. Lassie only barked it once.
Camp Snoopy is a children’s mini-theme park based on the comic strip “Peanuts.” The first was at Knott’s Berry Farm in California; there used to be one at the Mall of America.
All films in which mountains play a prominent role:
Anthrax is a thrash metal band that formed in NYC in 1981. Guitarist Scott Ian thought the name, spotted in a biology textbook, sounded “sufficiently evil.”
There is a popular image (apparently originating in a painting) of St. Bernards wearing a small cask of brandy around their necks to help warm people rescued in the mountains.
The Searchers is a John Ford Western starring John Wayne as a Civil War veteran searching for his niece (Natalie Wood) after she is stolen by Indians.
Cycle was a brand of dog food manufactured by Del Monte Foods. Cycle 1 was for puppies, Cycle 2 was for ages 1-7, etc.
For most of the past 100 years, matte paintings were hand painted on glass; more recently they have been digital effects added in post-production.
The theme to the 1963 film The Great Escape.
On the TV show Sanford and Son, when Fred Sanford wanted to control his son, he would fake a heart attack and call to his dead wife, “It’s the big one! I’m comin’, Lizabeth!”
Luckenbach, Texas, is home to the Luckenbach Dance Hall, which regularly hosts country-music concerts. Total population of the “town”: 3.
A reference to MST3K Episode 418, Attack of the Eye Creatures.
Souvlaki is the fast food of Greece: thinly sliced meat wrapped in a pita along with lettuce, tomato, onions, and tzatziki, a yogurt-cucumber sauce.
Each episode of House Party had a segment with this title, in which host Art Linkletter would interview a child; he eventually wrote two books based on the interviews.
Country singer Lyle Lovett is known for his wild shock of bushy hair. He has won four Grammy Awards and acted in a number of films.
Adolf Hitler set up the Hitler Youth to teach Nazi principles to young boys, who joined at 14 and “graduated” at 18 as a member of the Nazi Party and the German military.
In the 1975 film version of Tommy, this song was performed by Ann-Margret.
A bar mitzvah is a Jewish religious ceremony welcoming a boy to adulthood on his 13th birthday.
Cliffhanger starred Sylvester Stallone as a mountain ranger who gets mixed up with crooks searching for a lost cache of stolen money.
An imitation of the theme from the TV sitcom What’s Happening!!, composed by the famous Henry Mancini.
Hec Ramsey was a TV show that starred Richard Boone as an aging, turn-of-the-century detective.
“The Greatest Love of All” was originally a top 10 hit in 1977 for George Benson; a 1985 cover by Whitney Houston became a #1 hit.
A River Runs Through It is a novella by Norman Maclean about two brothers who love fly fishing.
A paraphrase of a line at the end of The Wizard of Oz, when Dorothy awakens in her bedroom.
Denver Pyle starred in several acclaimed films, including The Man Who Shot Liberty Valance and Bonnie and Clyde.
Snausages are a bite-sized dog treat shaped like tiny cocktail weenies.
Doctors no longer recommend the use of syrup of ipecac in the case of accidental poisoning—instead, call a poison control center.
“Taste it all” and “One awesome calorie” were short-lived slogans for Diet Coke in 1993.
One of the many conspiracy theories surrounding JFK’s assassination claims that his route through Dallas was changed to pass by the infamous “grassy knoll.”
